<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-754-824  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 754 824.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 9 1989 v23 n41 p120(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Survey says: bigger budget, more CASE. (computer-aided softwareengineering)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryan, Alan J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A Touche Ross and Co survey of 568 information services (IS)departments shows that computer-aided software engineering tools(CASE) are becoming more pervasive among larger corporations.andP;  Theaverage IS budget for CASE-using companies was $47.7 million,while the average IS budget for non-CASE users was $16.8 million.andO;Staff turnover was lower for non-CASE companies.andP;  CASE usersexpect to realize benefits in higher quality systems with less oreasier maintenance.andP;  They do not expect to realize cost savings.andO;Users in CASE organizations are more actively involved in allphases of the systems development cycle than non-CASE users.andO;Thirteen percent of the CASE-using IS managers said it has beenhighly integrated into their systems development strategy, whileabout 43 percent said it has been only slightly integrated or notat all.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Touche Ross and Co. (surveys).andO;Topic:     BudgetingSurveyComputer-Aided Software EngineeringInformation Services.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   IS managers rate integration of CASE technology. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>